conclusion: I love #JuliaLang , still use #Python a lot because of the ecosystem, and stopped using #RStats because in my usecases the upsides never outweigh the downsides.
For datascience and building deep learning models, there are a few realistic options when it comes to programming languages. I will compare #JuliaLang , #Python and #RStats üßµ1/n

Regarding the joy of coding in #JuliaLang , #Python or #RStats : I can get into a flow of coding with every language. They all have their own elegant tricks. However, if you work with a team, in production, I typically need more than elegance.
And: the "no free lunch theorem" still holds. There is no perfect solution for every usecase. If you are happy with your #RStats usecase, great. Never intended to deny that.

Usecase: my client uses #RStats and wants to let the whole company use their private notebook. They will need to pay 60k a year to use a Shiny dashboard as a company. I advise them to switch to #Python, and rewrite their scripts that are unmaintainable to begin with.

#RStats lovers might feel I'm too negative about R. I really see a usecase if you are teaching statistics or work in a small team and just do analytics on small data. The tidyverse is really a joy to work with: I enjoyed it myself too. Just not for every usecase.
